File: elot.info,  Node: Prerequisites,  Next: Install ELOT from MELPA,  Up: Installation

2.1.1 Prerequisites
-------------------

   • *Emacs 30.1 or later*.  ELOT uses ‘peg.el’, which became a built-in
     library in 30.1.
   • *Java 11 or later*, required by ROBOT.
   • *ROBOT (https://github.com/ontodev/robot)*, an OWL command-line
     tool.  Download ‘robot.jar’ from the ROBOT releases page and note
     its path.
   • *PlantUML (https://plantuml.com/)* (optional), for diagram
     rendering via ‘rdfpuml’.
   • *Protégé 5.6* (optional), for cross-checking ontologies in a GUI.


File: elot.info,  Node: Install ELOT from MELPA,  Next: Install ELOT from Git,  Prev: Prerequisites,  Up: Installation

2.1.2 Install ELOT from MELPA
-----------------------------

When ELOT is on MELPA:

     (use-package elot
       :ensure t)

   That is the whole installation.  ‘elot-mode’ is autoloaded.


File: elot.info,  Node: Install ELOT from Git,  Next: Point ELOT at ROBOT,  Prev: Install ELOT from MELPA,  Up: Installation

2.1.3 Install ELOT from Git
---------------------------

Until the MELPA recipe lands, clone the repository and add it to your
load path:

     git clone https://github.com/johanwk/elot ~/src/elot

   In your ‘init.el’:

     (add-to-list 'load-path "~/src/elot/elot-package")
     (require 'elot)


File: elot.info,  Node: Point ELOT at ROBOT,  Next: Verify,  Prev: Install ELOT from Git,  Up: Installation

2.1.4 Point ELOT at ROBOT
-------------------------

Set ‘elot-robot-jar-path’ to the absolute path of your downloaded
‘robot.jar’:

     (setq elot-robot-jar-path "~/bin/robot.jar")

   You can also customize it via ‘M-x customize-variable RET
elot-robot-jar-path’.


File: elot.info,  Node: Verify,  Prev: Point ELOT at ROBOT,  Up: Installation

2.1.5 Verify
------------

Open an Org file and run ‘M-x elot-mode’.  The ELOT menu appears in the
menu bar.  ‘M-x elot-version’ prints the loaded version.

   If something goes wrong, see *note Troubleshooting and FAQ:
Troubleshooting and FAQ.


