2.2 Your first ontology
=======================

In this chapter you build a tiny ontology of _pets_ from scratch.  By
the end you will have:

   • a working ‘pets.org’ file you can re-tangle and re-export at will,
   • a generated ‘pets.omn’ ontology in OWL Manchester Syntax,
   • the start of an HTML render of your ontology document.

   Time required: 15-20 minutes.

* Menu:

* Create the file::
* Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax::
* Sanity-check with ROBOT::
* Where to next::


File: elot.info,  Node: Create the file,  Next: Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax,  Up: Your first ontology

2.2.1 Create the file
---------------------

Create ‘pets.org’ anywhere in your filesystem and paste the skeleton
below.  Open it in Emacs and run ‘M-x elot-mode’.

     #+TITLE: A tiny ontology of pets
     #+AUTHOR: Your Name

     * Prefixes
     ,:PROPERTIES:
     ,:header-args:emacs-lisp+: :tangle no
     ,:END:

     #+name: prefix-table
     ,| prefix | uri                                            |
     ,|--------+------------------------------------------------|
     ,| ex     | http://example.org/pets/                       |
     ,| owl    | http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#                 |
     ,| rdfs   | http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#          |
     ,| skos   | http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#           |

     * ex:pets
     ,:PROPERTIES:
     ,:ID:       pets-ontology
     ,:ontology-iri: http://example.org/pets/
     ,:END:

     A small example ontology used by the ELOT tutorial.

     ** Classes
     *** ex:Animal
     A living creature.

     *** ex:Dog
     ,:PROPERTIES:
     ,:subclass-of: ex:Animal
     ,:END:
     A dog is an animal.

     *** ex:Cat
     ,:PROPERTIES:
     ,:subclass-of: ex:Animal
     ,:END:
     A cat is an animal.


File: elot.info,  Node: Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax,  Next: Sanity-check with ROBOT,  Prev: Create the file,  Up: Your first ontology

2.2.2 Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax
-------------------------------------

With point anywhere in ‘pets.org’, run ‘M-x elot-tangle’.  A file
‘pets.omn’ appears next to your Org source.  Open it; you should see
Manchester-syntax declarations for ‘ex:Animal’, ‘ex:Dog’ and ‘ex:Cat’.


File: elot.info,  Node: Sanity-check with ROBOT,  Next: Where to next,  Prev: Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax,  Up: Your first ontology

2.2.3 Sanity-check with ROBOT
-----------------------------

From a shell:

     robot report --input pets.omn --output pets-report.tsv

   ROBOT's report should be empty (or contain only INFO entries).
Errors mean ELOT generated something OWL does not like; see *note
Linting and syntax checking: Linting and syntax checking.


